# Lab 3: User Role Controlled by Request Parameter

**Difficulty:** Apprentice  
**Status:** ✅ Solved  
**OWASP Reference:** A01 - Broken Access Control

---

## Objective
Access the admin panel at /admin and delete the user carlos using
provided credentials: wiener:peter

---

## Vulnerability
Admin privilege controlled by a forgeable client-side cookie. The
application uses a cookie value of Admin=true/false to determine
whether a user has admin access — a value the user can freely modify.

---

## How I Found It
Logged in with the provided credentials (wiener:peter) and ran Burp
Suite in the background to capture all HTTP traffic. In the Target
tab I identified the /my-account request and inspected the request
headers. On line 3 I spotted a cookie set to Admin=false — a
client-controlled value the server was trusting to determine the
user's role.

![Burp Suite Target tab - Admin=false cookie discovered in HTTP history](/appsec-notes/access-control/lab3/lab3-cookie-admin-false-discovery.png)

---

## Exploitation
Sent the /my-account request to Burp Repeater. Modified the cookie
value from Admin=false to Admin=true. Changed the URL to
/admin/delete?username=carlos and hit Send. The server trusted the
modified cookie without verifying the user's actual role server-side
— returning a 302 redirect to /admin confirming the delete was
executed successfully.

![Burp Repeater - Modified Admin=true cookie and delete carlos request](/appsec-notes/access-control/lab3/lab3-repeater-delete-carlos.png)

---

## What I Learned
Cookies are stored client-side and can be freely modified by any
user. Never trust client-side data to make security decisions.
Admin roles and privileges must always be verified server-side
against the user's authenticated session — not read from a value
the user controls.

---

## The Fix
Store the user's role in a server-side session tied to their
authenticated identity. When a sensitive route like /admin is
requested, check the user's role from the server session — never
from a cookie or request parameter the client can modify.

---

## Tools Used
- Burp Suite Community Edition — Proxy, Target, Repeater